Presto on Spark uses temp storage for storing and distributing
broadcast tables. Spark driver performs the necessary threshold
checks on broadcast table and if the size is over the threshold,
the query fails with broadcast oom. The only way to fix this
failure is to disable broadcast join in the query.

As we are able to detect broadcast OOM on driver confidently,
we can just disable broadcast join, replan and resubmit the
query for execution. This can happen within the same spark
session itself and thus would not need any users intervention
for fixing such failures.', 'distinct': True, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/v-jizhang/presto/commits/e98b500aecf5909668b237c53cbaf65ff11884dd'}, {'sha': '1877f5aa3c7f9f09ef94b32246f7a5c4ecd56791', 'author': {'email': '65374769+sdruzkin@users.noreply.github.com', 'name': 'Sergii Druzkin'}, 'message': 'Optimize MAP type asserts in OrcTester', 'distinct': True, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/v-jizhang/presto/commits/1877f5aa3c7f9f09ef94b32246f7a5c4ecd56791'}, {'sha': 'd5ef9b65df15eddfae122805012a9c3ad27aec91', 'author': {'email': 'viswanadha@fb.com', 'name': 'Sreeni Viswanadha'}, 'message': 'Remove state from more scalar functions

'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': "Verifier is showing a regression in the latest release (0.272), with many queries failing with a `COLUMN_MISMATCH` error. This is caused by the commits in https://github.com/prestodb/presto/pull/17232 (https://github.com/prestodb/presto/commit/65ecdd6553c1cf476a6b9b8bc0ffd50678cdfdcd, https://github.com/prestodb/presto/commit/62b0d7b308e3b7b698389c5c6050c02301696b3a, https://github.com/prestodb/presto/commit/19e5853137efac6ea9e91eba9fe068017164de72, https://github.com/prestodb/presto/commit/a8d85317f5c3cb5efb7d1ffc93974d74630a9148, https://github.com/prestodb/presto/commit/0ae645b1bb8af1babc3e525552eea6d04496e221), which change the way we display results. Each of these commits lead to similar discrepancies in results, so we are reverting them as well.

Example:

Prod:
```
presto:infrastructure> select cast(round(100*53.6, 2) AS VARCHAR);
 _col0
--------
 5360.0
(1 row)
```

Test:
```
presto:infrastructure> select cast(round(100*53.6, 2) AS VARCHAR);
 _col0
--------
 5.36E3
```

For now we want to revert these changes to avoid breaking user's pipelines, as previous Presto versions gave different results.

Then, we can reenable this functionality behind a feature flag, with the default set to the current behavior.

Cherry-pick of commit
https://github.com/trinodb/trino/pull/212/commits/f086b525d66f0a59f7b8fe60173f2e4eed000a28

Early versions of the Apache ORC writer made the mistake of recording
timestamps from an epoch that was relative to the time zone of the
writer. This was fixed in later versions by recording the writer time
zone in the stripe footer. Hive 3.1 always writes using UTC.

Presto used a global configuration for the writer time zone, which
was needed to handle old files, but was never updated to use the time
zone from the stripe footer.

On read, Presto now uses the stripe value if present, otherwise it
uses the configured value. On write, Presto continues to write
timestamps using the configured time zone, but now records this value
when writing files.

Co-authored-by: David Phillips <david@acz.org>', 'distinct': True, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/v-jizhang/presto/commits/3f09bce7fe7132a032ee8e1a4df6c0ae64f3ae8a'}]}

https://github.com/trinodb/trino/pull/212/commits/f086b525d66f0a59f7b8fe60173f2e4eed000a28

Early versions of the Apache ORC writer made the mistake of recording
timestamps from an epoch that was relative to the time zone of the
writer. This was fixed in later versions by recording the writer time
zone in the stripe footer. Hive 3.1 always writes using UTC.

Presto used a global configuration for the writer time zone, which
was needed to handle old files, but was never updated to use the time
zone from the stripe footer.

On read, Presto now uses the stripe value if present, otherwise it
uses the configured value. On write, Presto continues to write
timestamps using the configured time zone, but now records this value
when writing files.

Co-authored-by: David Phillips <david@acz.org>

```

The intermediate type of avg function for all input types other than REAL is ROW
(DOUBLE, BIGINT), where double column stores the sum and bigint columns stores
the count. However, intermediate type of avg(REAL) is ROW(BIGINT, DOUBLE),
where sum and count and swapped. This makes it inconvenient to provide
matching implementation in Velox. This change is to align the intermediate
types for all input types.', 'distinct': True, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/v-jizhang/presto/commits/8c50171f3dc7df99050886ca87c8ffd3f5fa00ab'}, {'sha': '761cd55b974a47a91a16f60be5276b646c96cc45', 'author': {'email': 'jsoref@users.noreply.github.com', 'name': 'Josh Soref'}, 'message': 'Fix cleanup workflow reference

* Remove spurious strategy from non matrix workflows

* Name CI workflows', 'distinct': True, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/v-jizhang/presto/commits/761cd55b974a47a91a16f60be5276b646c96cc45'}, {'sha': '241adf197a88d6cac99d445463ce704be1b87348', 'author': {'email': 'ruslanmar@fb.com', 'name': 'Ruslan Mardugalliamov'}, 'message': 'Add join table reference check in JOIN ON clause

While it is permitted to omit the reference of the joining table in a
conditional join, the result of such join can lead to a cross join with
filter, which can harm the query execution performance. Often, such
queries are just a result of copy and paste from another join when
user updated the joining table name but forgot to update the join
condition.

This change will show the PERFORMANCE_WARNING to the user in cases
when JOIN ON clause misses the comparison expression with joining
table and other table.', 'distinct': True, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/v-jizhang/presto/commits/241adf197a88d6cac99d445463ce704be1b87348'}, {'sha': '7830670cb02fbcecf5f082b452864d8d3a06da30', 'author': {'email': 'adutta@fb.com', 'name': 'Amit Dutta'}, 'message': 'Throw proper error code when timezone is invalid from packDateTimeWithZone function.', 'distinct': True, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/v-jizhang/presto/commits/7830670cb02fbcecf5f082b452864d8d3a06da30'}, {'sha': '172763fa01ddccaa7ee0f4cc8379a4851b7e8768', 'author': {'email': 'fgwang7w@gmail.com', 'name': 'George Wang'}, 'message': 'refactor logic to support create TPC tables for HiveQueryRunner', 'distinct': True, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/v-jizhang/presto/commits/172763fa01ddccaa7ee0f4cc8379a4851b7e8768'}, {'sha': 'de18be1cf17968d16c5b6b4980bc22077ab96fdb', 'author': {'email': 'fgwang7w@gmail.com', 'name': 'George Wang'}, 'message': 'Add TPCDS schema to HiveQueryRunner

Before this change, the end of input after reading a JSON value
was not properly validated:
- if there were remaining characters which did not parse as JSON,
  exception was thrown. E.g. `'["correct JSON"]and more'` failed
- if there were remaining characters which formed a valid token,
  they were silently ignored. E.g. `'["correct JSON"]{and more'`
  succeeded and returned `'["correct JSON"]'`

After this change, any trailing characters are caught and reported
as error.

Co-authored-by: kasiafi <30203062+kasiafi@users.noreply.github.com>

Test plan - Added tests

{'push_id': 9226962231, 'size': 3, 'distinct_size': 3, 'ref': 'refs/heads/master', 'head': 'ae9f55968916f34fef2bb793f8b81b7142353c35', 'before': 'f7774e57a1d3c04c24d74066d67b754cc9a49a53', 'commits': [{'sha': 'bcf13da6a10f24a754ca1f635bba7c4be8bac8c7', 'author': {'email': 'athirupathi@fb.com', 'name': 'Arunachalam Thirupathi'}, 'message': 'Refactor null handling in ORC Dictionary writers

Before this change, nulls are tracked in dictionary indexes as negative
indexes. When they are converted to direct encoding or during stripe
flush they are written to PresentOutputStreams. In the final streams
nulls are represented using bit fields but in memory they are represented
as byte, short or int depending on the dictionary size.

Representing them as index had 8,16 or 32(byte, short or int) times overhead.
This caused the writers to OOM as dictionary buffered bytes count only
1/8th of a byte for nulls. The present stream has the same representation
whether it is direct or dictionary encoded data. This change now tracks the
Present stream in dictionary directly and when converting to direct, the
present stream responsibility is transferred to the direct writer.', 'distinct': True, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/v-jizhang/presto/commits/bcf13da6a10f24a754ca1f635bba7c4be8bac8c7'}, {'sha': '2081ec904c50a3e4fe863b2c38e6d6d1549512f6', 'author': {'email': 'chliang@uber.com', 'name': 'Chen'}, 'message': 'Add getDefaultBlockSize and getDefaultReplication to CachingFileSystem', 'distinct': True, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/v-jizhang/presto/commits/2081ec904c50a3e4fe863b2c38e6d6d1549512f6'}, {'sha': 'ae9f55968916f34fef2bb793f8b81b7142353c35', 'author': {'email': 'chunxut@twitter.com', 'name': 'Chunxu Tang'}, 'message': 'Refactor iceberg multi-catalog smoke tests', 'distinct': True, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/v-jizhang/presto/commits/ae9f55968916f34fef2bb793f8b81b7142353c35'}]}

Storage based broadcast join uses distributed storage for storing
broadcast table. Before broadcasting the data, driver will perform
a size check to ensure that the table size is under threshold. If
the table size is beyond threshold size, driver fails the query with
exceeded broadcast memory limit. This threshold can be overriden
using `spark_broadcast_join_max_memory_override` property and users
can override it to insanely high value. This would prevent the query
from failing in driver memory check but it will eventually fail on
executor with JVM OOMs.

This PR add two checks to prevent this kind of OOMs:
1. The first check is added in driver where threshold bytes is computed
using threshold = min(spark_broadcast_join_max_memory_override,
query_max_memory_per_node). This will max out the threshold to max
available memory and fail the query on driver if size goes beyond
`query_max_memory_per_node`

2. When hashtable is created on executors, entire data is read from
storage and stored in a list<page>. This data is then deserailized
which further inceased memory usage. While loading this data, memory
usage is not updated which means that if the table is huge, we will
keep loading the data until JVM OOMs. A memory callback is added in
this logic where after loading data from each file, a callback will
be made to update the memory usage so far. With this, EXECEEDED_MEMORY_LIMIT
error is thrown as soon as memory usage in executor goes beyond
`query_max_memory_per_node` while loading HT in memory', 'distinct': True, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/v-jizhang/presto/commits/ca90676880d4eea9f59180da30855c88e39f4647'}, {'sha': 'e3c9af6c4b386c4dd366e3fea4760a2a49592086', 'author': {'email': 'rongrong100@gmail.com', 'name': 'Rongrong Zhong'}, 'message': 'Enable cost based optimization by default

Cherry-pick of https://github.com/trinodb/trino/pull/6380:

Identifiers with characters such as @ or : are not being treated as
delimited identifiers, which causes issues when the planner creates
synthetic identifiers as part of the plan IR expressions. When the
IR expressions are serialized, they are not being properly quoted,
which causes failures when parsing the plan on the work side.

For example, for a query such as:

    SELECT try("a@b") FROM t

The planner creates an expression of the form:

    "$internal$try"("$INTERNAL$BIND"("a@b", (a@b_0) -> "a@b_0"))

The argument to the lambda expression is not properly quoted.

{'push_id': 9174347477, 'size': 1, 'distinct_size': 1, 'ref': 'refs/heads/maintain_quotedness', 'head': '1fda46d0a4b379c11a481f26f1d01e794e4a5394', 'before': 'c620eb843f12a6b3f445b45ff7c42dfd1591872c', 'commits': [{'sha': '1fda46d0a4b379c11a481f26f1d01e794e4a5394', 'author': {'email': 'jzhang@openteams.com', 'name': 'v-jizhang'}, 'message': 'Tighten allowed characters for non-delimited identifiers

Cherry-pick of https://github.com/trinodb/trino/pull/6380:

Identifiers with characters such as @ or : are not being treated as
delimited identifiers, which causes issues when the planner creates
synthetic identifiers as part of the plan IR expressions. When the
IR expressions are serialized, they are not being properly quoted,
which causes failures when parsing the plan on the work side.

For example, for a query such as:

    SELECT try("a@b") FROM t

The planner creates an expression of the form:

    "$internal$try"("$INTERNAL$BIND"("a@b", (a@b_0) -> "a@b_0"))

The argument to the lambda expression is not properly quoted.

Co-authored-by: Martin Traverso <mtraverso@gmail.com>', 'distinct': True, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/v-jizhang/presto/commits/1fda46d0a4b379c11a481f26f1d01e794e4a5394'}]}

In OrcWriter each column writer allocates its own scratch buffer for
compressing the data. When the file contains 1000's of columns this
adds upto more than 200MB. OrcWriter is not thread safe, so only one
compression buffer will be in use at any given time. This change
refactors the compression buffer to a pluggable pool implementation.
The default pool implementation is to reuse the last used pool.", 'distinct': True, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/v-jizhang/presto/commits/a20713619c73bed194882fef1341f7469dceba42'}, {'sha': '61ea2fa9dec3b5923a51b5834413314d474d7196', 'author': {'email': 'athirupathi@fb.com', 'name': 'Arunachalam Thirupathi'}, 'message': 'Use Factory method in OrcWriterOptions

while working on CompressionBufferPool realized that OrcWriterOptions
took in the implementation. presto-raptor for example shared the
same OrcWriterOptions for multiple writer. This required the
implementation to be thread safe or stateless. CompressionBufferPool
was neither and it introduced subtle race condition bugs. To avoid
future surprises moved the OrcWriterOptions to provide a factory.
OrcWriter will create an implementation and each OrcWriter will only
work with one implementation.', 'distinct': True, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/v-jizhang/presto/commits/61ea2fa9dec3b5923a51b5834413314d474d7196'}, {'sha': '60d644fbbafad63a694f05ef6dae0a465f2d5890', 'author': {'email': 'athirupathi@fb.com', 'name': 'Arunachalam Thirupathi'}, 'message': 'Option to disable string dictionary encoding in OrcWriter

column takes about 100 KB when initialized (40KB for row group index),

In Long dictionary encoding , unique values are encoded in dictionary
and indexes are stored in data stream. This encoding is beneficial when
the values are large numbers. Long dictionary encoding considered
all values as 8 bytes for raw bytes calculation and this resulted in
small values considered to dictionary stream.

Considered a stream that has only unique values from 1 to 10. Long
Dictionary encoding is not beneficial for these values. If the stream
has 10 unique numbers, but all of them are large numbers then long
dictionary encoding will be beneficial. This PR changes how raw bytes
estimate is calculated for the long dictionary.', 'distinct': True, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/v-jizhang/presto/commits/2be3158b47cc97d8e6bdbafcb1b531d5cc3ac9ec'}]}

native_type::= ASCII | BIGINT | BLOB | BOOLEAN | COUNTER | DATE

1. When stripe is flushed, OrcOutputBuffer holds the allocated memory.
This memory is unused until the next stripe flush. This memory can be
comparable in size to the dictionary memory, hence doubling the memory
required by the writer for the subsequent stripe flushes. Now
OrcOutputBuffer is reallocated for each stripe. Further as soon as the
dictionary is not required they are set to null.
2. When dictionar is abandoned, the hash buckets are not freed up.
This can be few megabytes per column and for multiple columns this
adds up. Now closeDictionary frees up the dictionary completely.

This change is a trade off, it reduces the memory required by writer
by 20% in most cases, while having marginal CPU impact.', 'distinct': True, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/v-jizhang/presto/commits/e580d2060e9b0b3a6b22519857e9c23c6685926e'}, {'sha': '1885f643b24d492ec65b0744ff9862cc2a212341', 'author': {'email': 'peu.sereno@gmail.com', 'name': 'Pedro Sereno'}, 'message': 'fix deltalake docs sql query render

ORC dictionary index size was based on the byte size of index. Index is
stored using varint encoding, so using byte boundary, does not capture
the size of the index bytes correctly. Used varint bit width to improve
the estimate of the index calculation.', 'distinct': True, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/v-jizhang/presto/commits/5424a61b29d582bf161913276c53f118fbbf287a'}, {'sha': 'a1fc5110d816205c4ab129aa3b0e40374f83dc0e', 'author': {'email': 'athirupathi@fb.com', 'name': 'Arunachalam Thirupathi'}, 'message': 'Reduce Slice Dictionary Memory usage

1. Reduce the segment size from 2^14 to 2^10. (65KB to 4KB).
2. On Reset, allocate a new DynamicSliceOutput. If the
DynamicSliceOutput has expanded by a lot, reset method used previously
preserved the allocated bytes and holding memory.
3. Reduce the default entries in dictionary from 10_000 to 1_024.
Segmented dictionary will allocate only 1024 entries at a time.', 'distinct': True, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/v-jizhang/presto/commits/a1fc5110d816205c4ab129aa3b0e40374f83dc0e'}, {'sha': 'f7f03f3601df11d87ab3aa2f86dd6257510e7233', 'author': {'email': 'athirupathi@fb.com', 'name': 'Arunachalam Thirupathi'}, 'message': "Reduce dictionary row group size

Dictionary row group consumes large amount of memory when the indexes
repeat. Consider a single column of String where the number of unique
values of string is 128. getBufferedBytes will return  number of
rows + size of dictionary. But the actual memory consumption would be
4 * number of rows + size of dictionary. On some tables with 100's of
columns, this is 100's of MB of difference and causing OOM issues.

Java generics does not work on primitive array so the code is
duplicated for byte, short and int. This introduces lot of code
duplication, but reduces the memory required significantly.", 'distinct': True, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/v-jizhang/presto/commits/f7f03f3601df11d87ab3aa2f86dd6257510e7233'}, {'sha': 'f24ffa7bc6e1cf4364081a03d8f26f3472b9766b', 'author': {'email': 'athirupathi@fb.com', 'name': 'Arunachalam Thirupathi'}, 'message': 'Refactor DictionaryRowGroup to top level class

Move DictionaryRowGroup to top level class in preparation of further
refactoring.', 'distinct': True, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/v-jizhang/presto/commits/f24ffa7bc6e1cf4364081a03d8f26f3472b9766b'}, {'sha': '3ea2ac2312c8466c33fc926e19950f449f3b79f5', 'author': {'email': 'athirupathi@fb.com', 'name': 'Arunachalam Thirupathi'}, 'message': 'Use segmented arrays for row group indexes

RowGroup in ORC by default is configured to 10,000 rows. If Table
contains nested types (Array[Array[String]]) each row can contain
upto tens of thousands of string and the number of indexes in a row
group can exceed millions. Using one large array and using integers
for all indexes cause Out Of Memory errors (a bigger problem for large
dictionary size configurations).

This PR introduces segments and dynamically use byte/short or only if
required to use ints for dictionary indexes.', 'distinct': True, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/v-jizhang/presto/commits/3ea2ac2312c8466c33fc926e19950f449f3b79f5'}, {'sha': '669a5ddcb76b3dd04feb19fc0675e97da339c058', 'author': {'email': '97547837+ericyuliu@users.noreply.github.com', 'name': 'ericyuliu'}, 'message': 'make UUID() a standard function
